    <!-- Quick Tips -->
    <string-array name="knitting_tips">
        <item>Always swatch before starting a new project — even if you think you know your gauge.</item>
        <item>Block your swatch the same way you plan to block your finished piece for an accurate gauge.</item>
        <item>To avoid a jog when knitting stripes in the round, lift the stitch from the row below onto the left needle on the second row of the new color.</item>
        <item>Keep your tension even for a professional finish on edges.</item>
        <item>Place a locking stitch marker every 20 stitches when casting on large numbers.</item>
        <item>Block your finished pieces — it makes a huge difference in the final look.</item>
        <item>Count your stitches at the end of every row when working lace patterns.</item>
        <item>Wind your yarn into a ball before starting — it prevents tangling.</item>
        <item>Use a lifeline every few rows in lace knitting — thread waste yarn through all stitches.</item>
        <item>Weave in ends as you go to avoid a pile-up at the end of your project.</item>
        <item>Always buy one extra skein — dye lots may vary between batches.</item>
        <item>Try knitting a gauge swatch in the round if your project is knit in the round — gauge can differ.</item>
        <item>Use stitch markers to separate pattern repeats — they make counting much easier.</item>
        <item>Read your entire pattern through before casting on to avoid surprises.</item>
        <item>Keep a project notebook to track your modifications and notes for future reference.</item>
        <item>When joining yarn, leave tails at least 15 cm long for secure weaving.</item>
        <item>Practice new techniques on a small swatch before committing to your project.</item>
        <item>Store your knitting in a project bag to keep it clean and prevent snags.</item>
        <item>Take breaks to stretch your hands and prevent repetitive strain injuries.</item>
        <item>Mark your place in the pattern with a sticky note or magnetic board.</item>
        <item>Use bamboo needles for slippery yarns — they grip the stitches better.</item>
        <item>When picking up stitches, use a needle one size smaller for a neater edge.</item>
        <item>Twist your stitches on the first round after casting on to prevent the cast-on from twisting.</item>
        <item>Measure your gauge after blocking, not before — many yarns change after washing.</item>
        <item>Alternate between two skeins every few rows to avoid visible dye lot differences.</item>
    </string-array>
</resources>
